%S A122672 1,1,3,2,11,12,40,68,192,395,1061,2432,6318,15417,39660,99550,256388,
%T A122672 654003,1689973,4355457,11305165,29347706,76527893
%N A122672 Number of primitive coronoid systems with n hexagons.
%C A122672 a(n) is the number of free ouroboros polyhexes, i.e., polyhexes in which every cell has exactly two neighbors. There are also 1 ouroboros polyhex with 3 cells and 1 with 6 cells, which are not included here because in Cyvin et al. (1991) it is required that "the inner perimeter should have a length of at least 10 edges". - _Pontus von Brömssen_, Jun 23 2026
%H A122672 Sven J. Cyvin, Jon Brunvoll, Björg N. Cyvin, John L. Bergan, and E. Brendsdal, <a href="https://doi.org/10.1007/BF00673438">The simplest coronoids: hollow hexagons</a>, Struct. Chem., 2 (1991), 555-566.
%H A122672 Johan Nilsson, <a href="/A122672/a122672.pdf">Illustrations for initial terms</a>.
%Y A122672 Cf. A359706 (ouroboros polyominoes), A397240 (ouroboros polyiamonds).
%K A122672 nonn,more
%O A122672 8,3
